<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-03">
  <title>Week 3</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-real-projective">
      <title>Real projective space</title>
      <p>
        It is worthwhile for us to spend some more time contemplating real projective space. Our prior work tells us that 
        <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> is built from two pieces: the upper hemisphere <m>S^n_+\cong B^n\cong \mathbb R^n</m> which is 
        homeomorphic to an open <m>n</m>-ball and Euclidean <m>n</m>-space, and a copy of <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>. These pieces 
        are glued together along the boundary of <m>B^n</m>, which is <m>S^{n-1}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        As it turns out, it will be advantageous to 
        package <m>B^n</m> and its boundary <m>S^{n-1}</m> into a single package, the closed <m>n</m>-disk
        <md>
          D^n := \{x\in \mathbb R^n\mid \lVert x\rVert\le 1\}.
        </md>
        This space comes equipped with a continuous inclusion of its boundary <m>S^{n-1}\hookrightarrow D^n</m> which is compatible 
        with the homeomorphism <m>S^n_{\ge 0}\cong D^n</m> given by projection onto the first <m>n</m> coordinates. 
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Each line through the origin in the <m>x_n=0</m> hyperplane passes through the <m>(n-1)</m>-sphere <m>S^{n-1}</m> twice at 
        antipodal points. It follows that
        <md>
          \mathbb{RP}^{n-1}\cong S^{n-1}/(x\sim -x),
        </md>
        which the reader may prove by contemplating
        <image width="80%">
          <description>
            <p>
             A commutative diagram relating <m>S^{n-1}</m>, its antipodal quotient, the punctured space
             <m>\mathbb{R}^n\setminus\{0\}</m>, the radial-scaling quotient, and <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzcd}
            	{S^{n-1}} \amp {S^{n-1}/(x\sim -x)} \\
            	{\mathbb R^n\smallsetminus\{0\}} \amp {(\mathbb R^n\smallsetminus \{0\})/(x\sim \lambda x)} \amp {\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}}
            	\arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
            	\arrow[hook, from=1-1, to=2-1]
            	\arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
            	\arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2]
            	\arrow[equals, from=2-2, to=2-3]
            \end{tikzcd}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        From this, we see that the restriction of the quotient map <m>\mathbb R^{n+1}\smallsetminus \{0\} \to \mathbb{RP}^n</m> to the 
        copy of <m>S^{n-1}</m> in the <m>x_n=0</m> hyperplane is a continuous quotient map onto <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>. It follows 
        that we have the commutative diagram
        <image width="50%">
          <description>
            A commutative square expressing how <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> is the union of <m>D^n</m> and <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m> 
            along <m>S^{n-1}</m>.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzcd}
            	{S^{n-1}} \amp {\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}} \\
            	{D^n} \amp {\mathbb{RP}^n.}
            	\arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
            	\arrow[hook, from=1-1, to=2-1]
            	\arrow[hook, from=1-2, to=2-2]
            	\arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2]
            \end{tikzcd}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </p>
      <p>
        It turns out that <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> is the "initial" space with which we can fill in the bottom right corner of the diagram. 
        This means that <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> is the <term>pushout</term> of <m>D^n</m> and <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m> along <m>S^{n-1}</m>, 
        a concept we will make precise momentarily.
      </p>
      <remark>
        <title>Coordinates for real projective space</title>
        <p>
          We can write <m>[x_0:x_1:\cdots:x_n]</m> for the equivalence class of 
          <m>(x_0,x_1,\ldots,x_n)\in \mathbb R^{n+1}\smallsetminus \{0\}</m> in
          <md>
            \mathbb{RP}^n = (\mathbb{R}^{n+1}\smallsetminus \{0\})/\mathbb R^\times.
          </md>
          As such, <m>[x_0:\cdots:x_n] = [\lambda x_0:\cdots:\lambda x_n]</m> for all <m>\lambda\in \mathbb R^\times</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In particular, 
          if <m>x_n\ne 0</m>, then
          <md>
            [x_0:x_1:\cdots:x_{n-1}:x_n] = [x_0/x_n:x_1/x_n:\cdots:x_{n-1}/x_n:1]. 
          </md>
          Points like this form the copy of <m>\mathbb R^n\cong B^n\subseteq D^n</m> in the above depiction of <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Meanwhile, the complement of this locus consists of points of the form <m>[x_0:\cdots:x_{n-1}:0]</m> with 
          <m>(x_0,\ldots,x_n)\ne 0</m>. These form a copy of <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>, precisely the one that appears in the top right 
          corner of the diagram above.
        </p>
      </remark>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-pushout">
      <title>Pushouts</title>
      <p>
        We now work in an arbitrary category <m>\mathsf C</m>. A <term>span</term> in <m>\mathsf C</m> is a diagram of the form 
        <m>X\leftarrow Z\to Y</m> where <m>X,Y,Z</m> are objects of <m>\mathsf C</m> and both arrows are morphisms of 
        <m>\mathsf C</m>.
      </p>
      <remark>
        <title>Span and cospan diagrams in categories</title>
        <p>
          There is a category <m>\mathsf S</m> with only three objects — call them <m>0,1,2</m> — and with exactly two non-identity 
          morphisms, <m>1\leftarrow 0\to 2</m>. (Make sure you understand how composition works in this category — there's not much 
          to define or check!) A span in a category <m>\mathsf C</m> is the same thing as a functor <m>\mathsf S\to \mathsf C</m>. 
          A <term>cospan</term> in <m>\mathsf C</m> is a functor <m>\mathsf S^{\text{op}}\to \mathsf C</m>, that is, a diagram in 
          <m>\mathsf C</m> of shape <m>X\to Z\leftarrow Y</m>.
        </p>
      </remark>
      <definition xml:id="def-pushout">
        <title>Pushouts</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>pushout</term> of a span in a category <m>\mathsf C</m> — when it exists — is an object <m>X\amalg_Y Z</m> of 
            <m>\mathsf C</m> equipped with morphisms <m>X\xrightarrow{i_X} X\amalg_Y Z\xleftarrow{i_Y} Y</m> such that the diagram
            <image width="50%">
              <description>
                A commutative square with span <m>X\leftarrow Z\to Y</m> in the top left and <term>cospan</term> 
                <m>X\xrightarrow{i_X} X\amalg_Y Z\xleftarrow{i_Y} Y</m> in the bottom right.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  {Z} \amp {Y} \\
                  {X} \amp {X\cup_Z Y}
                  \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
                  \arrow[from=1-1, to=2-1]
                  \arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
                  \arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2]
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            commutes in <m>\mathsf C</m> and if
            <image width="40%">
              <description>
                A commutative square with span <m>X\leftarrow Z\to Y</m> in the top left and <term>cospan</term> 
                <m>X\to W\leftarrow Y</m> in the bottom right.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  {Z} \amp {Y} \\
                  {X} \amp {W}
                  \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
                  \arrow[from=1-1, to=2-1]
                  \arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
                  \arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2]
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            is another commutative diagram in <m>\mathsf C</m> completing the original span to a square, then there is a 
            <alert>unique</alert> morphism <m>!\colon X\amalg_Y Z\to W</m> making the diagram
            <image width="60%">
              <description>
                A commutative square with span <m>X\leftarrow Z\to Y</m> in the top left and <term>cospan</term> 
                <m>X\to W\leftarrow Y</m> in the bottom right.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  Z \amp Y \\
                  X \amp {X\amalg_ZY} \\
                  \amp \amp W
                  \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
                  \arrow[from=1-1, to=2-1]
                  \arrow[from=1-2, to=2-2]
                  \arrow[from=1-2, to=3-3]
                  \arrow[from=2-1, to=2-2]
                  \arrow[from=2-1, to=3-3]
                  \arrow["{!}"{description}, from=2-2, to=3-3]
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            commute.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <exercise>
        <title>Pushouts are unique up to unique isomorphism</title>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>X\amalg_YZ</m> is unique up to unique isomorphism. This means that if <m>P</m>, equipped with morphisms 
          <m>X\to P\leftarrow Y</m>, is another object of <m>\mathsf C</m> satisfying the pushout universal property, then there 
          is a <alert>unique</alert> isomorphism <m>!\colon X\amalg_YZ\xrightarrow{\cong}P</m> such that
          <image width="60%">
            <description>
              A commutative square with span <m>X\leftarrow Z\to Y</m> in the top left and <term>cospan</term> 
              <m>X\to W\leftarrow Y</m> in the bottom right.
            </description>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzcd}
                \amp {X\amalg_ZY} \\
                X \amp\amp Y \\
                \amp P
                \arrow["{!}", from=1-2, to=3-2]
                \arrow["{i_X}", from=2-1, to=1-2]
                \arrow[from=2-1, to=3-2]
                \arrow["{i_Y}"', from=2-3, to=1-2]
                \arrow[from=2-3, to=3-2]
              \end{tikzcd}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          commutes.
        </p>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        The reader may check that for sets <m>A,B\subseteq X</m>, the pushout of the natural span 
        <m>A\hookleftarrow A\cap B\hookrightarrow B</m> is <m>A\cup B</m>. This is one sense in which we think of pushouts as 
        <alert>gluing</alert> the ends of a span together along the middle term, refined by the following proposition.
      </p>
      <p>
        We can also see that the pushout of <m>A\leftarrow\varnothing\to B</m> is <m>A\amalg B</m>, the disjoint union of <m>A</m> 
        and <m>B</m>. Recall that <m>A\amalg B := A\times \{0\}\cup B\times \{1\}</m>, where the labels <m>0,1</m> serve to separate 
        <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, ensuring there is no overlap among the two sets.
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-pushout-in-set">
        <title>Pushouts in Set</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The pushout of a span <m>X\xleftarrow{f} Z\xrightarrow{g} Y</m> in <m>\mathsf{Set}</m> is
            <md>
              X\amalg_ZY = (X\amalg Y)/(f(z)\sim g(z))
            </md>
            equipped with functions <m>i_X,i_Y</m> given by <m>i_X(x) = [x]</m> and <m>i_Y(y) = [y]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Given another cospan <m>X\xrightarrow{s} W\xleftarrow{t} Y</m> completing the span <m>X\xleftarrow{f} Z\xrightarrow{g} Y</m> to 
          a commutative square, we define
          <md>
            <mrow>!\colon X\amalg_ZY \amp \longrightarrow W</mrow>
            <mrow>[a] \amp \longmapsto \begin{cases} s(a) \amp \text{if }a\in X,\\ t(a) \amp \text{if }a\in Y. </mrow>
          </md>
          The reader may check that <m>!</m> is well-defined (because the square involving <m>W</m> commutes), that 
          <m>!\circ i_X = s</m> and <m>!\circ i_Y = t</m>, and that no other such function exists.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-pushout-in-top">
      <title>Pushouts in Top</title>
      <p>
        We are now prepared to study pushouts in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m>.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-pushout-top">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given spaces <m>X,Y,Z</m> and continuous functions <m>X\xleftarrow{f}Z\xrightarrow{g}Y</m>, the <term>pushout</term> 
            of <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> along <m>Z</m> (via <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>) is the pushout of the span 
            <m>X\xleftarrow{f}Z\xrightarrow{g}Y</m> in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Hmmm. That's not very satisfying, is it? And yet, via the universal property expressed in <xref ref="def-pushout" />, it's 
        exactly how we will construct continuous maps out of pushouts! And since pushouts are unique up to unique isomorphism, 
        this definition guarantees that at most one pushout (up to unique homeomorphism compatible with the diagram) exists.
      </p>
      <p>
        In order to get a better feel for pushouts in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m> and guarantee their existence, we must provide an explicit 
        construction.
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-pushout-in-top">
        <title>Pushouts exist in Top</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The pushout of a span <m>X\xleftarrow{f}Z\xrightarrow{g}Y</m> in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m> has underlying set given by the 
            pushout of underlying sets,
            <md>
              X\amalg_ZY = (X\amalg Y)/(f(z)\sim g(z));
            </md>
            its topology consists of sets <m>U\subseteq X\amalg_ZY</m> for which <m>i_X^{-1}U\subseteq X</m> and 
            <m>i_Y^{-1}U\subseteq Y</m> are open.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The form of the underlying set is already guaranteed by <xref ref="prop-pushout-in-set" />, and the reader may check that 
          the open sets above indeed form a topology. Let <m>Q</m> denote the associated space. Observe that 
          <m>i_X\colon X\to Q</m> and <m>i_Y\colon Y\to Q</m> are guaranteed to be continuous.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>W</m> be a topological space and suppose we are given continuous maps
          <m>u:X\to W</m> and <m>v:Y\to W</m> such that <m>u\circ f=v\circ g</m>.
          Since <m>Q</m> is the pushout of the underlying sets, there exists a unique function
          <m>h:Q\to W</m> with <m>h\circ i_X=u</m> and <m>h\circ i_Y=v</m>.
          It remains to show that <m>h</m> is continuous.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let <m>V\subseteq W</m> be open.  Then
          <md>
            i_X^{-1}\bigl(h^{-1}V\bigr) = (h\circ i_X)^{-1}(V) = u^{-1}(V)
          </md>
          and
          <md>
            i_Y^{-1}\bigl(h^{-1}V\bigr) = (h\circ i_Y)^{-1}V = v^{-1}V.
          </md>
          Since <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are continuous, both <m>u^{-1}V</m> and <m>v^{-1}V</m>
          are open in <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, respectively.  Therefore <m>h^{-1}V</m> is open in <m>Q</m> by
          definition of the topology, which proves that <m>h</m> is continuous.
          Uniqueness of <m>h</m> as a continuous map follows from uniqueness of the underlying
          function in <xref ref="prop-pushout-in-set" />.
        </p>

        <p>
          Thus <m>Q</m> together with <m>i_X</m> and <m>i_Y</m> satisfies the pushout
          universal property in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m>, so pushouts exist and are given by the stated
          construction.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <definition xml:id="def-coproduct-in-top">
        <title>Coproducts</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The <term>coproduct</term> of spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, denoted <m>X\amalg Y</m>, is the pushout of the unique 
            span of the form <m>X\leftarrow \varnothing\to Y</m>. In particular, <m>X\amalg Y</m> has underlying set the disjoint 
            union of <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> and its open subsets <m>U\subseteq X\amalg Y</m> are precisely those for which <m>U\cap X</m> 
            and <m>U\cap Y</m> are open.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example>
        <title>The circle as a pushout</title>
        <p>
          Recall that <m>S^0 = \{\pm 1\}\subseteq \mathbb R</m> is the 0-sphere, which includes into <m>D^1 = [-1,1]</m> as its boundary. 
          The circle <m>S^1</m> is the pushout of <m>D^1\leftarrow S^0\to D^1</m>. Indeed, <m>D^1\amalg_{S^0}D^1</m> consists of two 
          disjoint intervals — the north semicircle and south semicircle — glued together left endpoint to left endpoint and right 
          endpoint to right endpoint. (It follows from definitions that the pushout admits a continuous bijection to <m>S^1</m>. Later, 
          we will have a general theorem guaranteeing a continuous bijection from a compact space to a Hausdorff space is a homeomorphism. 
          We will write "by <m>C\to H</m>" to designate this caveat.)
        </p>
      </example>
      <example>
        <title>Spheres as pushouts</title>
        <p>
          Simiarly, the <m>n</m>-sphere is the pushout of <m>D^n\leftarrow S^{n-1}\to D^n</m> (by <m>C\to H</m>). One copy of <m>D^n</m> 
          forms the upper hemisphere, and the other is the southern hemisphere, glued together along the equator <m>S^{n-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </example>
      <example>
        <title>Two pushout presentations of projective space</title>
        <p>
          We have already discussed how to present <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> as the pushout of 
          <m>D^n\leftarrow S^{n-1}\to \mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>. But we can also describe <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> as the union of
          <md>
            U_0 = \{[x_0:x_1:\cdots:x_n]\mid x_0\ne 0\}
          </md>
          and
          <md>
            U_1 = \{[x_0:x_1:\cdots:x_n] \mid x_1\ne 0\}.
          </md>
          There are homeomorphisms <m>\varphi_i\colon U_i\xrightarrow{\cong}\mathbb R^n</m> given by taking <m>[x_0:x_1:\cdots:x_n]</m> to 
          either <m>(x_1/x_0,\ldots,x_n/x_0)</m> (when <m>i=0</m>) or <m>(x_0/x_1,x_2/x_1,\ldots,x_n/x_1)</m> (wnen <m>i=1</m>). 
          The intersection <m>U_0\cap U_1</m> is homeomorphic (via <m>\varphi_0</m>) to 
          <m>(\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\})\times \mathbb R^{n-1}</m>. It follows (by <m>C\to H</m>) that <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> is also the 
          pushout of a span of the form <m>\mathbb R^n\leftarrow (\mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\})\times \mathbb R^{n-1}\to \mathbb R^n</m> 
          where the first map is the standard inclusion, and the latter is given by
          <md>
            (u_1,u_2,\ldots,u_n)\longmapsto (1/u_1,u_2/u_1,\ldots,u_n/u_1).
          </md>
        </p>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>
    
  </subsection>
</section>
